Exploratory analysis of remote sensing SIF data

D. Emin

December 20, 2018

Summary

  • Most SIF data from HyPlant is normally distributed
  • Outliers are located mainly along the edges of agricultural fields
  • average SIF values for fields located in higher and lower terrace showed significant difference

Introduction

HyPlant is an airborne hyperspectral sensor developed specifically for SIF retrieval over larger areas. By delivering SIF data at spatial resolution between 0.5 and 3 m, it occupies an intermediate spatial scale between ground based point spectrometer and operational and future satellite sensors. Indeed, HyPlant have been used to study the regional variability of SIF across variety of ecosystems.

HyPlant sensor have been operated on an aircraft over the Selhausen study site anually since 2014 with various scientific goals - from instrument testing to spatial SIF characterisation. It delivers high quality SIF data at least since 2016 and there is ground truth collected also at least 2016. By flying at two altitudes the HyPlant sensor delivers data at 3 and 1 meter resolution. The former resolution covers the northern half of TERENO Monitoring Observatory “Eifel/Lower Rhein valley”, while the latter higher spatial resolution is used to cover a smaller subsection - the Selhausen Study site.

At the nominal spatial resolution of 1 m2 - data from HyPlant enables analysis of the within field variability of SIF inside agricultural fields in the region. This chapter focuses on characterization of SIF data retrieved by HyPlant sensor for three consecutive years. This descriptive statistics should ensure not only about the quality of the SIF retrieval but also define typical SIF values for different crop types, inform about the specific spatial distribution of SIF inside the study area and point to probable cause of observed phenomenon.

The following analysis is made on 2016 HyPlant data only on sugar beet fields. By constraining the descriptive overview first to only one crop we can focus on regional and environmental factors. later we will expand the analysis to include all (green) crops in the region.

It includes the following sub-chapters :

  • Spatial distribution of outliers
  • exploratory data analysis at the nominal scale (1m)
  • exploratory data analysis at the field scale (field average)
  • spatial analysis in relation to soil conditions and terrace

Data

We will use a raster stack of Selhausen study area containing all relevant layers - SIF, SIF ratio, Vegetation indicies and LAI, as well as auxilary information.

Spatial distribution of outliers in Selhausen

The processing algorythm relies heavily on existence of bare soil pixels in the obesrvational frame. In some few cases the computation can yield negative values (normally around 0). To account for these we will first explore the raw HyPlant image and plot the distribution of SIF values.

We can see that predominant portion of SIF Ratio values in the lower percentile and some few outliers in the tail, SIF contains negative values which need to be accounted for. Also Simple ratio VI has outlier in the high end. We will adopt the following exclusion criteria: ** SIF values are negative, SIF ratio is above 2, or SR is above 40.** Before excluding those ouliers we will calculate their proportion in the data set and see what affect removing them has on the first and second moments (mean and median).

What is the proportion of negative SIF values in our dataset? How many pixels have negative values in O2A, in O2B, in either one of both SIF bands, and in both SIF bands?

There are a total of 22279 negative SIF (O2A) values, which amounts to 1.98 % of pixels in the entire sugar beet dataset.

There are a total of 34447 negative SIF (O2B) values, which amounts to 3.06 % of pixels in the entire sugar beet dataset.

There are a total of 42990 negative SIF values in at least one of O2A and O2B bands. This amounts to 3.82 % of pixels in the entire sugar beet dataset.

There are a total of 13736 negative SIF values in both O2A and O2B bands. This amounts to 1.22 % of pixels in the entire sugar beet dataset.

How does exclusion of negative values affect the mean SIF estimate?

Using all values, mean SIF760 = 2.291 [mW.s-1.nm-1.m-2].

After excluding negative values, mean SIF760 = 2.315 [mW.s-1.nm-1.m-2].

The difference is 0.024 [mW.s-1.nm-1.m-2].

What is the proportion of excluded data points? The proportion of excluded data points is 0.9 %.

We will shows the location of outliers inside sugar beet fields For easier visualisation, we will zoom-in to a smaller section of the study area and assume uniformity of the observed distribution, e.g. the process governing outlier distribution is the same across the whole study area. Now lets explore the spatial distribution of negative SIF values and SIF ratio.

SIF ratio above 2

Since SIF ratio is calculated as SIF687/SIF760 and SIF687 is almost always smaller than SIF760 in remote sensing scenario, we expect SIF ratio values predominantly in the range between 0 and 1. To allow for the possibility of inverse magnituted of both SIF peaks, eg. red SIF being larger than far-red SIF, we will keep SIF ratio values smaller than 2. This is a conservative filter, which eliminates small percentage of values spread across a wider range.

Bellow we show the spatial distribution of SIF ratio outliers, reclasified into two classes - bellow and above the cut down value of 2.

We see that all SIF ratio values above 2 are located around the edges of the fields. This points to the possible explanation of high SIF ratio is edge of the field, where no vegetation is growing.

SIF 760 negative values

SIF 687 negative values

Most negative value are located long the edges of the fields. There are some exceptions at SIF687 band, specifically in smaller fields.
